            <!-- Explanation -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How the lap time calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is built for drivers, engineers, and sim racers who
                need quick, accurate lap time and stint calculations. It
                supports three common scenarios:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Estimate lap time from track length and average speed.</li>
                <li>
                  Compute average lap time from total race time and number of
                  laps.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Plan a race stint with target lap time, number of laps, and
                  pit stops.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Lap time from distance and speed</h3>
              <p>The core relationship is simply distance divided by speed:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Lap time (hours)</strong> = distance / speed</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>distance is the lap length (km or miles)</li>
                  <li>speed is the average speed over the lap (km/h or mph)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>To convert hours to seconds:</p>
                <p>\( t_{\text{sec}} = t_{\text{hours}} \times 3600 \)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator handles unit conversions automatically (km ↔ mph,
                miles ↔ km) and displays lap time in a racing-friendly format
                like <code>1:45.500</code>.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Average lap time from total time and laps</h3>
              <p>
                If you know the total race or session time and the number of
                laps completed, the average lap time is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Average lap time</strong> = total time / number of
                  laps
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Enter your race duration in hours, minutes, and seconds, plus
                the lap count. The tool returns:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Average lap time in <code>mm:ss.sss</code></li>
                <li>
                  The same value in pure seconds for engineering analysis or
                  telemetry tools
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Race / stint planning with pit stops</h3>
              <p>
                For race strategy, you often start from a target lap time and
                want to know how long a stint will take, and how much pit stops
                will cost in total time.
              </p>
              <p>The calculator uses:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( T_{\text{driving}} = t_{\text{lap}} \times N_{\text{laps}}
                  \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( T_{\text{pits}} = N_{\text{pits}} \times t_{\text{pit}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( T_{\text{total}} = T_{\text{driving}} + T_{\text{pits}} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                It also generates a simple pace table showing cumulative time at
                the end of each lap, which is useful for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Estimating when you will catch or be caught by other cars
                </li>
                <li>Planning fuel windows and tire strategy</li>
                <li>Comparing different target lap times</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Typical use cases</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Track days:</strong> Estimate lap times from your
                  expected average speed to set realistic goals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sim racing:</strong> Plan stints and pit windows for
                  league races or endurance events.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Engineering analysis:</strong> Convert race results
                  into average lap times for performance benchmarking.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Lap time calculator FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How accurate is a lap time based only on average speed?</h3>
              <p>
                Using distance and average speed gives a good first-order
                estimate, but it ignores braking, acceleration, and cornering
                details. Real lap times depend on the speed profile around the
                circuit, tire grip, traffic, and track conditions. Use this as a
                planning tool, then refine with real telemetry.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for running, cycling, or swimming laps?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The math is identical. Just treat the “lap distance” as
                your track or loop length and “speed” as your average pace. The
                units are generic, so you can think in km/h, mph, or convert
                from pace if needed.
              </p>

              <h3>What time formats does the calculator accept?</h3>
              <p>The stint planner accepts:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><code>mm:ss</code> (e.g. <code>01:45</code>)</li>
                <li>
                  <code>mm:ss.s</code> or <code>mm:ss.sss</code> (e.g.
                  <code>1:45.5</code>, <code>1:45.532</code>)
                </li>
                <li>Pure seconds (e.g. <code>105.5</code>)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How should I estimate pit lane time loss?</h3>
              <p>
                Time loss per pit stop is the total time from pit entry line to
                pit exit line, including driving at pit speed limit and
                stationary time. If you have timing data, use the difference
                between a normal lap and a lap with a pit stop. Otherwise, use a
                conservative estimate (e.g. 20–30 seconds) and adjust after
                practice.
              </p>
            </section>
